LAGOS – The Office of the United Nations Special Rapporteur for Freedom of Religion has collaborated with the Khartoum International Religious Freedom Leaders in Sudan to advocate for and advance freedom to practice religions of choice in the country. Co-chairs of the Khartoum International Religious Freedom (IRF), Tawfig Osman Saleh and Dr. William Devlin of REDEEM and their team, were invited by the United Nations to help coordinate and lead the consultation, which held via Zoom meeting on Monday, at the Paradise Hotel in Khartoum, titled: “The Khartoum Consultation on the Status of Religious Freedom, 2022,” A statement released by Saleh and Devlin said: “We appreciate and welcome the opportunity to be invited to continue our relationship with the UN FORB Special Rapporteur. Iran Needs Nuclear Energy, Not Nuclear Bomb – Khamenei Iran Fixes June 2021 For Presidential Election “Today’s consultation was another step forward for Religious Freedom in Sudan. As our beloved nation of Sudan continues to experience difficulty, we are thankful that all the Sudanese people are committed to working together to advance religious freedom, even in spite of our difficulties. Let us all pray for Sudan and especially the Christians. The Khartoum IRF has already established the East Africa IRF Secretariat, which will reach out to six nations, beginning with Eritrea and South Sudan.” Joining the Khartoum Consultation on the Zoom call was His Excellency, Ahmed Shaheed, the United Nations Special Rapporteur for Freedom of Religion or Belief (FORB). The Special Rapporteur was an invited guest and speaker October 20-21, 2020, when the Khartoum IRF Roundtable (RT) held one of the largest religious freedom consultations on the African continent.